{
  "presentation": {
    "topics": [
      {
        "id": "title",
        "title": "Title Slide",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "title",
            "title": "Cassandra & Distributed Systems ()",
            "subtitle": "Mastering Availability, Scalability, and Consensus <br> The Architecture of NoSQL at Scale"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "cassandra-foundations",
        "title": "1. Cassandra Foundations",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "1. What is Apache Cassandra?",
            "subtitle": "A high-performance, distributed NoSQL database."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Core Philosophy",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🌐",
                  "text": "<strong>Decentralized:</strong> Every node in the cluster is identical."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "📈",
                  "text": "<strong>Elastic Scalability:</strong> Add more nodes to increase throughput linearly."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🛠️",
                  "text": "<strong>Fault Tolerant:</strong> Data is replicated across multiple nodes."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Designed to handle massive amounts of data across many servers without a single point of failure."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "distributed-theory",
        "title": "2. Distributed Theory",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "2. The CAP Theorem",
            "subtitle": "Understanding the trade-offs of distributed systems."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "CAP: Consistency, Availability, Partition Tolerance",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "⚡",
                  "text": "<strong>Cassandra Choice:</strong> AP (Availability + Partition Tolerance)."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "⚖️",
                  "text": "<strong>Tunable Consistency:</strong> You can choose consistency level per query."
                }
              ],
              "title": "You can only have two out of three in a network partition."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "gossip-protocol",
        "title": "3. The Gossip Protocol",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "3. Cluster State",
            "subtitle": "How nodes talk to each other."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Peer-to-Peer Communication",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🗣️",
                  "text": "<strong>Epidemic Protocol:</strong> Information spreads like a virus through the cluster."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "⏱️",
                  "text": "<strong>Convergence:</strong> State reaches all nodes in log(N) time."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Every node periodically chats with a few other nodes to share state."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Phi Accrual Failure Detector",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📉",
                  "text": "<strong>Adaptive:</strong> Uses historical heartbeat data to predict if a node is likely dead."
                }
              ],
              "title": "How Cassandra knows if a node is 'down'."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "partitioning-hashing",
        "title": "4. Data Partitioning",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "4. Dividing Data",
            "subtitle": "The Ring and the Hash."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Consistent Hashing",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "⭕",
                  "text": "<strong>Token Ring:</strong> Each node is responsible for a range of tokens."
                }
              ],
              "code": "PartitionKey -> Murmur3 Hash -> Token",
              "title": "Partition keys are hashed into a 128-bit range (The Ring)."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Virtual Nodes (vnodes)",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🍕",
                  "text": "<strong>Load Balancing:</strong> Helps in rebalancing when adding/removing nodes."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Splitting a node's token range into many small pieces."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "write-path",
        "title": "5. The Write Path",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "5. Writing Data",
            "subtitle": "Designing for extreme write-throughput."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The CommitLog",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🗒️",
                  "text": "<strong>Safety first:</strong> Write returns success only after the CommitLog is flushed."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Sequential, append-only log for durability."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The MemTable",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🧠",
                  "text": "<strong>Speed:</strong> Updates are handled in memory before disk flush."
                }
              ],
              "title": "In-memory sorted buffer (LSM-Tree head)."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "SSTable Flush",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📑",
                  "text": "<strong>Immutability:</strong> SSTables are never edited; only compacted later."
                }
              ],
              "title": "When MemTable is full, it's flushed to disk as an SSTable."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "read-path",
        "title": "6. The Read Path",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "6. Reading Data",
            "subtitle": "How Cassandra finds data across multiple files."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The Multi-File Search",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🔍",
                  "text": "<strong>Process:</strong> Check MemTable -> Check Row Cache -> Check Bloom Filters -> Check SSTables."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Cassandra might need to check multiple SSTables for a single row."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Bloom Filters",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🔬",
                  "text": "<strong>Benefit:</strong> Drastically reduces expensive disk I/O."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Probabilistic exclusion of SSTables."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "tunable-consistency",
        "title": "7. Tunable Consistency",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "7. Consistency Levels",
            "subtitle": "The power of the CAP theorem in your hands."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Read & Write Levels",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "1️⃣",
                  "text": "<strong>ONE:</strong> Fast, but risk of stale data."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "⚖️",
                  "text": "<strong>QUORUM:</strong> Majority response; ensures linearizability if W+R > N."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "♾️",
                  "text": "<strong>ALL:</strong> Highest consistency, lowest availability."
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "compaction-strategies",
        "title": "8. Compaction Mechanisms",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "8. Compaction",
            "subtitle": "Managing the proliferation of SSTables."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Why Compact?",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🧹",
                  "text": "<strong>Garbage Collection:</strong> Removing tombstoned (deleted) data."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Merging multiple SSTables into one to improve read performance and reclaim space."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "STCS vs LCS",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📈",
                  "text": "<strong>STCS:</strong> SizeTiered Compaction Strategy (Optimized for writes)."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🏗️",
                  "text": "<strong>LCS:</strong> Leveled Compaction Strategy (Optimized for reads)."
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "anti-entropy",
        "title": "9. Anti-Entropy & Repair",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "9. Cluster Healing",
            "subtitle": "Ensuring all replicas are in sync."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Hinted Handoff",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📦",
                  "text": "<strong>Recovery:</strong> When the node comes back, the hints are delivered."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Storing writes locally for a node that is temporarily down."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Read Repair",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🚑",
                  "text": "<strong>Mechanism:</strong> If replicas differ, the latest data is written to the stale nodes."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Repairing stale replicas during a read query."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Merkle Trees",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🌳",
                  "text": "<strong>Validation:</strong> Used during full cluster repair ('nodetool repair')."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Comparing data across nodes efficiently using hash trees."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "data-modeling",
        "title": "10. CQL & Data Modeling",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "10. Data Modeling",
            "subtitle": "The NoSQL way: Query-First Design."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Partition Key vs Clustering Key",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🔑",
                  "text": "<strong>Partition Key:</strong> Determines which node stores the data."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "📁",
                  "text": "<strong>Clustering Key:</strong> Determines the sort order within the partition."
                }
              ],
              "code": "PRIMARY KEY (user_id, posted_at)"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The Golden Rule",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🚫",
                  "text": "<strong>No Joins:</strong> Denormalize data to avoid cross-node communication."
                }
              ],
              "title": "One Table Per Query."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "replication-architecture",
        "title": "11. Replication & Snitches",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "11. Topology",
            "subtitle": "How Cassandra understands your data center."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Replication Strategies",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🏢",
                  "text": "<strong>NetworkTopologyStrategy:</strong> Multi-DC aware replication."
                }
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The Snitch",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📡",
                  "text": "<strong>GossipingPropertyFileSnitch:</strong> Best for production cloud environments."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Determines relative node proximity for routing queries."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "maintenance",
        "title": "12. Maintenance & Nodetool",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "12. Operations",
            "subtitle": "Keeping the clusters healthy."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Nodetool",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🛠️",
                  "text": "<strong>status:</strong> Check node health."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🔄",
                  "text": "<strong>repair:</strong> Perform full cluster sync."
                }
              ],
              "title": "The swiss army knife for Cassandra operators."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "paxos-lwt",
        "title": "13. Lightweight Transactions (Paxos)",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "13. Strong Consistency",
            "subtitle": "How Cassandra achieves 'Linearizability'."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "What are LWTs?",
            "box": {
              "code": "INSERT INTO users (...) IF NOT EXISTS;",
              "title": "Compare-and-Set (CAS) operations using the Paxos consensus protocol."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The Paxos Phases",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🏁",
                  "text": "<strong>Prepare/Promise:</strong> Propose a change to the cluster."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🗳️",
                  "text": "<strong>Accept/Acknowledge:</strong> Agreement on the proposal."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🚀",
                  "text": "<strong>Commit/Learn:</strong> Finalizing the change."
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "indexing-sei",
        "title": "14. Advanced Indexing (SAI)",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "14. Secondary Indexing",
            "subtitle": "Querying non-partition keys efficiently."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Storage Attached Indexing (SAI)",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🏗️",
                  "text": "<strong>Efficiency:</strong> Highly space-efficient, decoupled from the storage engine."
                }
              ],
              "code": "CREATE INDEX ON users(email) USING 'sai';",
              "title": "The modern way to index in Cassandra 4.0+."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "performance-tuning",
        "title": "15. Performance Engineering",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "15. Tuning",
            "subtitle": "Squeezing every drop of throughput."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "JVM Tuning (G1GC)",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🧹",
                  "text": "<strong>G1GC:</strong> The standard collector for large Cassandra heaps."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🧠",
                  "text": "<strong>Off-heap:</strong> Moving caches outside the JVM to reduce GC pressure."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Why garbage collection matters for NoSQL latency."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Disk I/O Strategies",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "⚡",
                  "text": "<strong>SSD Optimization:</strong> Cassandra is designed to leverage random access speed."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🗜️",
                  "text": "<strong>Compression:</strong> LZ4 is the default for a reason."
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "cass-maintenance",
        "title": "16. Operational Excellence",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "16. Operations",
